Date: Wed, 9 Apr 1997 14:02:54 -0500
Via: Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy <BSE-L@RZ.UNI-KARLSRUHE.DE>
From: Karyn Bischoff <bischof@okway.okstate.edu>
Concerning the ability or lack thereof to rule out toxic causes of
"spongiform" encephalopathies:
I'm only a veterinary toxicology resident, but I can say with some
confidence that most of the toxins that would be associated with the type of
neural lesions described would be difficult or impossible to detect. This is
because that quite a bit of time usually passes from exposure to onset of
clinical signs, and death follows some time later. By then, due to
metabolism and excretion, the toxic compound is frequently at levels below
our ability to detect. I believe that most of the time this sort of
diagnosis is based on history of exposure--which may be a difficult thing to
obtain!
---
Karyn Bischoff
Oklahoma Animal Disease Diagnostic Laboratory
Oklahoma State University
